2.4. Analysis; Regression model

The regression model below has three explanatory variables: Attitude, stra and surf. I chose the variables that had the highest absolute correlation with Examination Points (=outcome variable).

# create a multiple regression model with explanatory variables: Attitude, stra and surf and outcome variable: Points
mreg_model <- lm(Points ~ Attitude + stra + surf, data = students2014)

# print out a summary of the model
summary(mreg_model)

## Call:
## lm(formula = Points ~ Attitude + stra + surf, data = students2014)

Looking at the results: It seeems that Attitude explains the Exam Points the most (statistically significant p-value), which is in line with the plots seen above (the regression line has the strongest angle compared to the ones in plots visualizing the correlation between points and stra/surf). In other words, in the Coefficients section, stra and surf are not considered to be significant by the model because their p-value is higher than 0.05. Keeping them does not provide any additional value to the model, so regression model using only Attitude would be best.


The R-Square of the model means the proportion of variance explained by the model, which is 0.21 = the model explains 21 % of the Examination Points. If we use only Attitude in the model (below), the R-Square is 0.19 (not much changed when stra and surf removed from the model), which means Attitude towards statistics explains 19 % of the Examination points. Further we can see that for every one Point increase, the value of Attitude increases 0.35.

# create a multiple regression model with explanatory variable Attitude and outcome variable Points
reg_model <- lm(Points ~ Attitude, data = students2014)

3.3. Choosing the variables


Assignment: Choose 4 interesting variables in the data and for each of them, present your personal hypothesis about their relationships with alcohol consumption.

There are many interesting variables to choose from, but here I wanted to examine the possible effect of the family socioeconomic status (SES) and family relationships on students alcohol consumption, so I chose the parents education (Medu = mothers education, Fedu = fathers education), home address type (address = urban or rural) and the quality of family relationships (famrel). Income would have been a nice addition, but that information was not collected. My hypothesis is that higher education of the parents, living in urban area and having a good family relations might predict using less alcohol. Iâm interested to see if mothers and fathers education have differ on the effect they have on their childrens alcohol consumption. Although alcohol use is a bit difficult to predict with different socioeconomic variables, since for example drinking wine with meals is usually more typical in middle-high and high-income families, when drinking beer and other similar beverages might be more common in low-income families, at least in some countries. Letâs see what this data has to say about the relationship of family SES and relationships with students alcohol consumption.

3.5. Logistic regression

Letâs make a logistic regression with the values we have. The goal is to see whether variables predict binary value of high consumption of alcohol.


# logistic regression model and summary of the model
m <- glm(high_use ~ Medu_cat + Fedu_cat + address + famrel, data = alc, family = "binomial")
# summary of the model
summary(m)

## Fedu_cat    1.0037127 0.7636785 1.3207660
## addressU    0.6136974 0.3632679 1.0456781
## famrel      0.7544783 0.5918643 0.9600937

The Coefficients table shows that only quality of family relations (famrel) is statistically significant (p<0.05). The coefficient estimate of the variable famrel is negative (b=-0.2817) meaning that on step increase in family relation quality decreases the probability of being high-user of alcohol to 0.72. The living area (address) correlates with the high use of alcohol, but it is not statistically significant (p=0.0695).
The odds ratio (OR) for famrel is 0.754, which means the odds for being in a high alcohol consumption group decreases as the family relations gets better (CI: 0.592-0.960). Other variables include 1 in their confidence interval, meaning there is no difference in parents education groups nor living area when trying to predict wheter student is a high alcohol consumer.


Itâs a bit boring to have only one variable predicting the high alcohol use in this model, but below Iâm exploring the predictive power of the model, mainly to learn how it is done.

# include the only significant variable
m2 <- glm(high_use ~ famrel, data = alc, family = "binomial")

# predict() the probability of high_use
probabilities <- predict(m2, type = "response")

# add the predicted probabilities to 'alc' and use the probabilities to make a prediction high_use
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)

# tabulate the target variable versus the predictions and probabilities
print(table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction))
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE
##    FALSE   259
##    TRUE    111
print(table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction) %>% prop.table() %>% addmargins())
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE Sum
##    FALSE   0.7 0.7
##    TRUE    0.3 0.3
##    Sum     1.0 1.0

As you would guess, this model does not give much more information compared to the simple guessing from the previous bar plots and frequency tables. The model predicts about one third wrong (111). If I would have had more time, I would have explored more variables and try to create a better model.


Finally, letâs calculate a loss function for the predictions and K-fold cross validation:

# define a loss function (mean prediction error)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

# call loss_func to compute the average number of wrong predictions in the (training) data
# note: in the RStudio editor, this outputs [1] 0.2891892 - I didn't have time to find out why it is rounded to 0.3 when knitted
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)
## [1] 0.3
# call loss_func to compute the average number of wrong predictions in the data when everyone is a high-user
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = 0)
## [1] 0.3
library(boot)
# K-fold cross validation 
cv <- cv.glm(data = alc, cost = loss_func, glmfit = m2, K = nrow(alc))

# average number of wrong predictions in the cross validation
cv$delta[1]
## [1] 0.3162162


There is a 30 % chance of a student being wrongly classified as not being a high user in this model. The error rate 0.289 is not better than the model explored in the exercises and it is just barely better than just assuming everyone is a non-high user.

Variable meaning
crim per capita crime rate by town
zn proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.
indus proportion of non-retail business acres per town.
chas Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise).
nox nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per 10 million).
rm average number of rooms per dwelling.
age proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940.
dis weighted distances to five Boston employment centres
rad index of accessibility to radial highways
tax full-value property-tax rate per $10,000
ptratio pupil-teacher ratio by town
black 1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town
lstat lower status of the population (%)
medv median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000âs

# create a quantile vector of crim 
bins <- quantile(boston_scaled$crim)

4.3. Dividing the dataset

Below Iâll divide the dataset into âtrainâ and âtestâ sets, so that random 80 % of the data is in the âtrainâ set and the rest is in the âtestâ set.

# number of rows in the Boston dataset (needed to define 80 % of the rows)
n <- nrow(boston_scaled)

# choose randomly 80% of the rows
ind <- sample(n,  size = n * 0.8)

4.4. Linear discriminant analysis

Next Iâll fit linear discriminant analysis (LDA) to the dataset. Linear discriminant analysis finds the (linear) combination of the variables that separate the target variable classes. The target can be binary or multiclass variable. Here Iâm using categorical crime as a target variable and the rest of the variables as predictors.

# linear discriminant analysis
lda.fit <- lda(crime ~ ., data = train)

# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  graphics::arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

# plot the lda results 
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 2)


Percentage separations achieved by the first discriminant function is 95 %, second is 3.7 % and the third is 1.3 %. Biplot based on LD1 and LD2 shows that high is mostly separated from others around LD1 6 and LD2 0 (only few med_high overlapping), when other groups have more overlap. Based on arrows, rad explains clearly the high group, whereas other predictors are in the middle.

Next Iâll run k-means algorithm on the dataset âboston_scaled2â.

# k-means clustering
km <- kmeans(boston_scaled2, centers = 4)

# plot the Boston dataset with clusters (first 7 variables)
pairs(boston_scaled2[1:7], col = km$cluster)

# plot the Boston dataset with clusters (last 7 variables)
pairs(boston_scaled2[8:14], col = km$cluster)

It can be seen from the visualizations, that the clusters overlap quite a lot.


Next Iâll investigate the appropriate number of clusters:

set.seed(123)

# determine the number of clusters to be 10
k_max <- 10

# calculate the total within sum of squares
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(boston_scaled2, k)$tot.withinss})

# visualize the results
qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line')

The line always declines with the count of clusters and the idea is to identify where is a appropriate number of clusters (where is the breaking point of the most added value from an additional cluster). It seems that the line starts to level off at around two, and after that the line continues roughly on the same angle. I decided to use two clusters (decided between two and three) and fit the model again. We can see that it is much easier to distinguish the two clusters from each other.

set.seed(123)

# k-means clustering
km <- kmeans(boston_scaled2, centers = 2)

# plot the Boston dataset with clusters (first 7 variables)
pairs(boston_scaled2[1:7], col = km$cluster)

# plot the Boston dataset with clusters (last 7 variables)
pairs(boston_scaled2[8:14], col = km$cluster)
